Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: This section describes Box Containers, which arrange child controls vertically or horizontally and utilize the Stretch Ratio property.
Box Containers
Arranges child controls vertically or horizontally (via HBoxContainer and VBoxContainer). In the opposite of the designated direction (as in, vertical for a horizontal container), it just expands the children.

These containers make use of the Stretch Ratio property for children with the Expand flag set.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the GridContainer node for arranging child controls in a grid layout.
Grid Container arranges child controls in a grid layout. The amount of columns must be specified. It uses both the vertical and horizontal expand flags.
---CHUNK---
Document: gui_containers.rst
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the MarginContainer and how its margins are controlled by the theme.

Margin Container
Child controls are expanded towards the bounds of this control (via MarginContainer). Padding will be added on the margins depending on the theme configuration.

Again, keep in mind that the margins are a Theme value, so they need to be edited from the constants overrides section of each control.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: This section describes the TabContainer, a UI element that allows stacking multiple child controls and switching between them using tabs.
Tab Container
Allows you to place several child controls stacked on top of each other (via TabContainer), with only the current one visible.

Changing the current one is done via tabs located at the top of the container, via clicking.

The titles are generated from the node names by default (although they can be overridden via TabContainer API).

Settings such as tab placement and StyleBox can be modified in the TabContainer theme overrides.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes how Split Containers arrange child controls and allow resizing via grabbers.
Split Container arranges child controls vertically or horizontally and creates grabbers between them (via HSplitContainer and VSplitContainer). It respects both horizontal and vertical expand flags, as well as Stretch Ratio. The grabbers can be dragged around to change the size relation between the children.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the PanelContainer control node, its purpose, and how it's used in UI layouts.

PanelContainer
A container that draws a StyleBox, then expands children to cover its whole area, respecting the StyleBox margins. It respects both the horizontal and vertical sizing options.

This container is useful as a top-level control, or just to add custom backgrounds to sections of a layout.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the FoldableContainer, a UI element that can hide or show its child controls.
FoldableContainer
A container that can be expanded/collapsed. Child controls are hidden when it is collapsed.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the ScrollContainer node and its usage for displaying content larger than its own bounds.
ScrollContainer
Accepts a single child node. If the child node is bigger than the container, scrollbars will be added to allow panning the node around. Both vertical and horizontal size options are respected, and the behavior can be turned on or off per axis in the properties. Mouse wheel and touch drag (when touch is available) are also valid ways to pan the child control around. As in the example above, one of the most common ways to use this container is together with a VBoxContainer as child.
---CHUNK---
Document: gui_containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the AspectRatioContainer node, which maintains the aspect ratio of its children when resized.
AspectRatioContainer is a container that arranges its child controls while automatically preserving their proportions when the container is resized. It offers several stretch modes for adjusting child control sizes relative to the container: "fill," "width control height," "height control width," and "cover." This container is beneficial for dynamic and responsive UIs where child elements must scale proportionally without distorting their intended shapes across various screen sizes.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers Tutorial
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Explains the purpose and behavior of the FlowContainer in Godot's UI system.
FlowContainer is a container that arranges its child controls either horizontally or vertically (via HFlowContainer and via VFlowContainer). When the available space runs out, it wraps the children to the next line or column, similar to how text wraps in a book. It is useful for creating flexible layouts where the child controls adjust automatically to the available space without overlapping.
---CHUNK---
Document: gui_containers
Path: godot/tutorials/ui/gui_containers.rst
Summary: Describes the CenterContainer node and its function in centering child controls.
CenterContainer is a container that automatically keeps all of its child controls centered within it at their minimum size. It ensures that the child controls are always aligned to the center, making it easier to create centered layouts without manual positioning.
---CHUNK---
Document: GUI Containers
